Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.00,0:00:26.00,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,{\fs100\t(,\fs110)\frz1\fad(3000,500)\fsp0\fscx120\pos(960,800)\b0\shad0\bord0}地          球          脉          动
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.90,0:00:34.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球上只有3%的水是淡水\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Only 3 percent of the water on our planet is fresh.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.42,0:00:41.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可是这些珍贵的淡水中却充满了惊奇\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Yet these precious waters are rich with surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.98,0:00:59.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所有陆地生命归根结底都依赖于淡水\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}All life on land is ultimately dependent upon fresh water.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.50,0:01:18.25,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,{\fs125\fsp6.5\fad(1000,1000)\pos(965,1200)}淡        水        资        源
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.25,0:01:31.75,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,{\fs60\fsp5\fad(1000,1000)\pos(960,1080)\bord0\shad3}画 外 音\N{\fs90}大卫 · 爱登堡   爵士
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.38,0:01:32.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,神秘的委内瑞拉平顶山区\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The mysterious tepuis of Venezuela -
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.34,0:01:38.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一个孤立于丛林之上的的山地高原\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}isolated mountain plateaus rising high above the jungle.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.26,0:01:53.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里是亚瑟·柯南·道尔的著作 《失落的世界》的灵感源泉\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This was the inspiration for Arthur Conan Doyle's 'Lost World,'
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.18,0:01:56.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一个想象中的史前世界\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}an imagined prehistoric land.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.38,0:02:10.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里伫立着数千年来暴风骤雨 雕凿成的奇形怪状的石塔\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Here, strange towers of sandstone have been sculptured over the millennia by battering wind and torrential rain.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.06,0:02:27.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水蒸发成水蒸气从海面升起\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Moisture rising as water vapour from the surface of the sea
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.22,0:02:30.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,接着被风带到内陆\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}is blown inland by wind.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.78,0:02:45.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,途经山脉的时候 水气被迫抬升\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}On reaching mountains, the moisture is forced upwards
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.82,0:02:51.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,逐渐冷却 汇聚成云 最后形成降雨\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and as it cools, it condenses into cloud and finally rain -
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.06,0:02:54.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这便是所有淡水的来源\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the source of all fresh water.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.22,0:03:09.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里全年几乎每天都会降下热带暴雨\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There is a tropical downpour here almost every day of the year.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.26,0:03:25.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,淡水之旅就是从这些高山之巅开始的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Fresh water's journey starts here, high in the mountains.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.30,0:03:44.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,涓涓细流汇集成泱泱大河\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Growing from humble streams to mighty rivers
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.54,0:03:48.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,行程数百英里回到大海\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}it will travel hundreds of miles to the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.90,0:04:29.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,安赫尔瀑布——世界上落差最大的瀑布\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Angel Falls, the highest waterfall in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.18,0:04:48.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,流水不间断地从将近1000米的高处落下\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Its waters drop unbroken for almost a thousand metres.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.14,0:04:59.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,具有如此这般高度的瀑布\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Such is the height of these falls
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.22,0:05:03.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在水还未落到恶魔谷底之前\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that long before the water reaches the base in the Devil's Canyon
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.42,0:05:07.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,便已被吹散成雾霾\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}it's blown away as a fine mist.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.78,0:05:42.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,上游地段的山涧充满活力\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In their upper reaches, mountain streams are full of energy.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.42,0:05:48.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,溪流汇聚成河\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Streams join to form rivers,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.42,0:05:49.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,随着力道的积聚\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}building in power,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.94,0:05:51.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,形成激流\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}creating rapids.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.66,0:06:03.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里的水较冷\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The water here is cold.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.74,0:06:07.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,营养物质不多 但含氧量却很高\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Low in nutrients, but high in oxygen.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.82,0:06:13.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,生活在急流中的少数几种动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The few creatures that live in the torrent
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.06,0:06:15.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,得有办法固定自己以保住性命\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}have to hang on for dear life.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.86,0:06:21.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,无脊椎动物统治着上游河段\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Invertebrates dominate these upper reaches.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.02,0:06:24.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是鱼蛉 其扁平的身体 能减少水的冲击力\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The hellgrammite, its body flattened to reduce drag,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.78,0:06:28.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,并依靠浓密的鳃从水中过滤氧气\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}has bushy gills to extract oxygen from the current.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.22,0:06:37.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,蚋的幼虫靠钩环固定自己\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Black fly larvae anchor themselves with the ring of hooks,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.86,0:06:42.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,即使不小心松脱了\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but if these become unstuck,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.90,0:06:46.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们还有一根坚韧的“安全索”\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they're still held by a silicon safety line.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.30,0:07:03.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些动物拥有在急流中生存的先天优势\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There are advantages to life in the fast stream -
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.14,0:07:09.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,拟匙指虾只需趴在河底  用它们的扇形前臂从流水中过滤出食物颗粒\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}bamboo shrimps can just sit and sift out passing particles with their fan-like forearms.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.02,0:07:34.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,通常 山涧提供的食物 只能维持小型动物生存\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Usually, these mountain streams only provide enough food for small animals to survive.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.90,0:07:38.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可是在日本 每当春雪消融之际\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But with the spring melt here in Japan
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.14,0:07:41.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一种怪物便在巢窟中苏醒\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}monsters stir in their dens.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.34,0:07:53.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大鲵——世界上最大的两栖动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Giant salamanders, world's largest amphibian,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.70,0:07:56.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,几乎能长到2米长\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}almost two metres long.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.38,0:08:03.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们是这些冰水中唯一的大型掠食动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They're the only large predator in these icy waters.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.62,0:08:10.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,夜幕降临 它们开始捕猎\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They begin their hunt at night.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.90,0:08:29.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大鲵的新陈代谢十分缓慢\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These salamanders have an exceptionally slow metabolism.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.34,0:08:33.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们能活80多年 因此长得十分巨大\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Living up to 80 years they grow into giants.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.82,0:08:52.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可供大鲵捕食的鱼非常稀少\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The fish they hunt are scarce
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.62,0:08:56.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而且它们的视力也很差\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and salamanders have poor eyesight.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.46,0:09:01.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可是它们头上和身上的感官突起\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But sensory nodes on their head and body
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.30,0:09:05.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,能觉察出最轻微的水压变化\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}detect the slightest changes in water pressure.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.94,0:09:17.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,由于没有竞争\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Free from competition,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.02,0:09:21.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些大家伙得以独自享用美食\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}these giants can dine alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.10,0:09:37.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大鲵的收获通常都比较少\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Pickings are usually thin for the salamanders,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.86,0:09:43.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而世界上的高山河流每年都将 迎接成千上万的来访者\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but every year some of the world's high rivers are crowded by millions of visitors.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.22,0:09:53.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鲑鱼来了\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The salmon have arrived.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.98,0:10:05.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是世界上规模最大的淡水鱼洄游\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is the world's largest fresh water fish migration.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.50,0:10:14.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鲑鱼穿越整个北半球  从海洋回到它们的产卵地\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Across the northern hemisphere salmon, returning from the ocean to their spawning grounds,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.86,0:10:18.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,奋力逆流而上数百英里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}battle their way for hundreds of miles upstream.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.30,0:10:28.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,只因上游很少有捕食鱼卵 和鱼苗的掠食者\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Up here, there are fewer predators to eat their eggs and fry.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.10,0:10:57.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一只灰熊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}A grizzly bear.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.50,0:11:01.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它已经很久没有打牙祭了\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}From famine to feast -
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.74,0:11:03.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,早就盼着这个机会\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}he's spoilt for choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.58,0:11:13.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这只加拿大熊很特别\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This Canadian bear is very special -
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.18,0:11:16.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它学会了潜水捕猎\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}he's learnt to dive for his dinner.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.66,0:11:34.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但要想在深水中捕获鲑鱼可不太容易\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But catching salmon in deep water is not that easy
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.58,0:11:37.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,熊崽们还要很多东西要学\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and the cubs have lots to learn.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.58,0:12:16.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鲑鱼每年都会到河里产卵\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The annual arrival of spawning salmon
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.22,0:12:20.00,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,于是这些平常只能勉强维持众多动物生计的高山河流\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}brings huge quantities of food into these high rivers
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.00,0:12:23.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,终于有了提供饕餮大餐的机会\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that normally struggle to support much life.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.54,0:12:40.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,尽管高山河流的生物量相对较少  它们却有能力改变地形\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Although relatively lifeless, the power of the upland rivers to shape the landscape
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.90,0:12:45.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在河流扮演的角色中 这才是最主要的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}is greater than any other stage in a river's life.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.78,0:12:51.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们借助地心引力  成为地球上最大的侵蚀力量\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Driven by gravity, they're the most erosive forces on the planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.98,0:12:58.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在过去的500万年中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}For the past 5 million years
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.62,0:13:03.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,亚利桑那州的科罗拉多河 冲走了大量沙石\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Arizona's Colorado river has eaten away at the desert's sandstone
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.46,0:13:06.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,形成一个巨大深邃的峡谷\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}to create a gigantic canyon.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.90,0:13:18.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它的深度超过1英里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It's over a mile deep
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.98,0:13:23.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最宽的地方达17英里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and at its widest it's 17 miles across.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.58,0:13:39.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这就是大峡谷\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Grand Canyon.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.86,0:14:02.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这条河冲蚀出了世界上最长的峡谷系\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This river has cut the world's longest canyon system -
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.58,0:14:08.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在太空中也能清楚地看到 这条长达1000英里的沟壑\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}a 1,000 mile scar clearly visible from space.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.06,0:14:35.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,河流离开山区之后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}As rivers leave the mountains behind,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.74,0:14:40.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,河水渐渐变暖 养育的动物也多了起来\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they gradually warm and begin to support more life.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.78,0:14:53.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,印度河里住着世界上最具社会性的水獭\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Indian rivers are home to the world's most social otter -
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.62,0:14:59.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,印度水獭的一个家族可多达17名成员\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}smooth-coated otters form family groups up to 17 strong.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.66,0:15:14.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,集体“按摩”不仅能清洁它们的皮毛\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Group rubbing not only refreshes their coats,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.38,0:15:17.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,也能增强群体内部团结\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but strengthens social bonds.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.62,0:15:28.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当它们去捕鱼时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}When it comes to fishing
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.26,0:15:31.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,群体合作能保证它们屡战屡胜\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}there is real strength in numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.78,0:15:48.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,小水獭在4个月大时就开始学习捕鱼\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Fishing practice begins when the cubs are four months old.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.62,0:16:11.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,只有成年水獭才具备 捕鱼所需的速度和灵巧\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Only the adults have the speed and agility needed to make a catch.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.34,0:16:53.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,成年水獭把“战利品”与幼崽一起分享  小家伙们立刻抢成一团\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Adults share their catches with their squabbling cubs.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.50,0:17:06.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大部分水獭都是独自生活\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Most otters are solitary,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.74,0:17:11.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是这些富饶温暖的水域 足以养活大型家族\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but these rich warm waters can support large family groups
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.22,0:17:14.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,甚至更大的掠食动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and even bigger predators.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.38,0:17:39.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,4米长的恒河鳄 能轻松捕获一只落单的水獭\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Mugger crocodiles, four metres long, could easily take a single otter.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.22,0:18:06.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不过集合起来的水獭颇有胆量\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But, confident in their gangs,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.58,0:18:10.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,反而会主动骚扰这些大块头的爬行动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the otters will actively harass these great reptiles.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.98,0:18:31.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,群体作战通常会取得胜利\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Team play wins the day.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.18,0:18:46.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,马拉河蜿蜒地穿过东非平原\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Mara river, snaking across the plains of East Africa.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.22,0:18:49.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,由于地势平坦\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}As the land flattens out
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.90,0:18:53.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,河水流速变慢 没有了原来的破坏力\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}rivers slow down and lose their destructive power.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.34,0:18:57.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,河流中带着大量的泥沙\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Now they are carrying heavy loads of sediment
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.78,0:19:00.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水变得很浑浊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that stains their waters brown.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:12.98,0:19:16.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一队队的角马正在迁徙途中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Lines of wildebeest are on their march.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:21.18,0:19:26.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每年都会有将近200万只角马 横越塞伦盖蒂平原\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Each year nearly two million animals migrate across the Serengeti plains
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.46,0:19:29.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,去寻找新鲜草场\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}in search of fresh green pastures.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.78,0:19:31.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,对于这群饥渴难耐的角马来说\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}For these thirsty herds
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.54,0:19:35.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,河流不仅是唯一能解渴的重要水源\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the rivers are not only a vital source of drinking water,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:35.02,0:19:38.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,也是充满危险的关隘\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but also dangerous obstacles.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.94,0:20:02.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里是非洲一处最大的尼罗鳄聚集地\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is one of the largest concentrations of Nile crocodiles in Africa,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.22,0:20:06.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些大怪物能长到5米多长\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}giants that grow over five metres long.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.46,0:20:26.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鳄鱼凭着记忆得知 角马已经来了\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}From memory, the wildebeest are coming
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.06,0:20:28.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不出所料 它们纷纷下水\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and gather in anticipation.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.10,0:21:35.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鳄鱼的巨口像捕兽铗一般紧咬住猎物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The crocodile's jaws snap tight like a steel trap -
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.30,0:21:38.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一旦被它逮住 猎物再无逃脱的机会\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}once they have a hold, they never let go.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.58,0:21:55.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它得花上一个多小时 才能淹死这只成年公角马\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It took over an hour to drown this full-grown bull.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.98,0:22:04.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,为了突袭猎物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}To surprise their prey
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.90,0:22:08.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,鳄鱼必须以闪电般的速度出击\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}crocodiles must strike with lightning speed.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.10,0:22:39.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在这里 生与死只有一线之隔\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Here, only the narrowest line separates life from death.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.58,0:23:17.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大部分河流都汇入大海\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Most rivers drain into the sea,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.30,0:23:21.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,可有些河流的终点却是大型湖泊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but some end their journey in vast lakes.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.34,0:23:30.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,全球湖泊淡水储量比江河多20倍\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Worldwide lakes hold twenty times more fresh water than all the rivers.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.66,0:23:37.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,东非大裂谷内有着3个世界上最大的淡水湖\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The East African Rift Valley holds three of the world's largest:
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.54,0:23:41.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,马拉维湖、坦噶尼喀湖 以及维多利亚湖\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Malawi, Tanganyika, and Victoria.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.50,0:23:46.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,马拉维湖是这3个湖泊中最小的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Lake Malawi, the smallest of the three,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.38,0:23:48.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,却仍比威尔士还要大\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}is still bigger than Wales.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:01.30,0:24:07.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,生活在这个热带湖泊里的鱼类 比其它湖泊都要丰富\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Its tropical waters teem with more fish species than any other lake.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:07.74,0:24:10.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里有850多种不同的慈鲷\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There are 850 different cichlids alone,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.06,0:24:18.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们都是从一个数千年前 即被隔绝在此的祖先进化而来的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}all of which evolved from just one single ancestor isolated here thousands of years ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.94,0:24:36.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些2米宽的土丘是鱼儿们的杰作\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These two-metre wide craters are fish-made.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.78,0:24:51.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,雄鱼一丝不苟地维护着坑巢  因为这里正是求爱的场所\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Fastidiously maintained by the males, these bowls are courtship arenas.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.26,0:25:07.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,慈鲷是尽心尽职的父母\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Cichlids are caring parents.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.30,0:25:16.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们将鱼苗含在嘴里  这是一种保护它们的有效方法\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Brooding young in the mouth is a very effective way of protecting them.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.62,0:25:21.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,马拉维湖也是个危机四伏的地方\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This lake can be a dangerous place.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.78,0:25:39.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,到了晚上 掠食性的长颌鱼纷纷 游出它们白天潜伏的石缝\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}After dark, predatory dolphin fish emerge from their daytime lairs among the rocks.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.26,0:25:49.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们像是一群鲨鱼  一边游一边寻找熟睡中的慈鲷\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Like packs of sharks, they're on the prowl for sleeping cichlids.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.38,0:25:59.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些鱼用电在黑暗中捕猎\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In the darkness these electric fish hunt
Dialogue: 0,0:25:59.94,0:26:05.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们在身体周围形成电场  并感知其变化\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}by detecting distortions in the electric field they create around their bodies.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.38,0:26:28.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一旦慈鲷切入电场  立刻就会成为捕食的对象\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Any cichlid that trenches out will be snapped up.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:48.42,0:26:54.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,马拉维湖底是一个深达700多米的深渊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The floor of Lake Malawi drops 700 metres into an abyss.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.78,0:27:08.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这个死亡地带成了 幽蚊幼虫躲避天敌的庇护所\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Here, in this dead zone the larvae of lake fly midges hide out away from predators.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.62,0:27:14.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每到雨季 它们便充气浮上水面\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In the rainy season they balloon up to the surface
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.58,0:27:17.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然后经历一场不可思议的变化\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and undergo a magical transformation.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.10,0:27:31.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,黎明时分 第一只成蚊破蛹而出\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}At dawn the first adult midges start to break out.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.50,0:27:41.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,不久 成百上千万只新羽化的幽蚊 全都扇动着翅膀飞到空中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Soon, millions upon millions of newly hatched lake flies are taking to the wing.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:51.74,0:27:57.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,早期探险家看到这种湖面上“冒烟”的情景  还以为是湖底着了火\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Early explorers told tales of lakes that smoked, as if on fire.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.74,0:28:02.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些高达数百米的螺旋型“烟”柱\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But these spiralling columns hundreds if metres high
Dialogue: 0,0:28:02.58,0:28:05.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其实是正在交配的幽蚊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}are mating flies.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.46,0:28:20.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,幽蚊完成交配之后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Once the flies have mated,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.10,0:28:22.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,便会一起落到水面\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they will all drop to the water surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.58,0:28:25.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,产下卵 然后死去\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}release their eggs and die.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.06,0:28:38.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,马拉维湖看起来像大海一样辽阔\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Malawi may look like an inland sea,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.22,0:28:42.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但它远比不上世界上最大的湖泊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but it's dwarfed by the world's largest lake -
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.38,0:28:46.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,东西伯利亚的贝加尔湖\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Baikal in Eastern Siberia.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.82,0:29:00.00,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,贝加尔湖长400英里 深度超过1英里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}400 miles long and over a mile deep,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.00,0:29:06.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,其中淡水储量占到了全球江河湖泊淡水总量的1/5\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Baikal contains one fifth of all the fresh water found in our planet's lakes and rivers.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.38,0:29:15.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每年中总有5个月  湖面被1米厚的冰层覆盖\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}For five months of the year it's sealed by an ice sheet over a metre thick.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.54,0:29:33.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,贝加尔湖是世界上最古老的湖泊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Baikal is the oldest lake in the world
Dialogue: 0,0:29:33.30,0:29:38.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,尽管生存条件恶劣  生命仍在这个与世隔绝的地方得到了兴盛\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and, despite the harsh conditions, life flourishes here in isolation.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.46,0:29:44.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,湖里80%的物种 在地球上其它地方都不存在\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}80 percent of its species are found nowhere else on Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:44.18,0:29:48.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,包括世界上唯一的淡水海豹\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}including the world's only fresh water seal.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:54.74,0:29:55.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有了这种海豹\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}With this seal
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.94,0:29:58.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,再加上海底森林一般的海绵\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and its marine-like forests of sponges
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.74,0:30:02.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,贝加尔湖看起来 更像是海洋 而不是湖泊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Baikal seems more like an ocean than a lake.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:21.02,0:30:27.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这种长得像虾一样的甲壳动物 是一种大型端足类动物 它有老鼠那么大\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}There are shrimp-like crustaceans - giant amphipods - as large as mice.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.86,0:30:36.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们是湖里不可或缺的“清洁工”\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They are the key scavengers in this lake.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:36.26,0:30:42.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,由于湖水过于寒冷  分解尸体的细菌很难在此存活\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The water here is just too cold for the bacteria that normally decompose the dead.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.62,0:30:58.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大部分河流并非止于湖泊\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Most rivers do not end in lakes
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.86,0:31:02.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而是一直奔向大海\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}but continue their journey to the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.70,0:31:11.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,地球上的超级大河 毫无疑问就是亚马逊河\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The planet's indisputable super-river is the Amazon.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.50,0:31:20.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它的水量是世界十大江河中 其余9条大河的总和\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}It carries as much water as the next top-ten biggest rivers combined.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.58,0:31:28.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它发源于秘鲁安第斯山区  其干流穿越整个巴西\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Rising in the Peruvian Andes, its main trunk flows eastwards across Brazil.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.82,0:31:33.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,全部流域面积达到南美洲的1/3\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}On its way the system drains a third of South America.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.58,0:31:38.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,最终 在经过4000英里的流程之后\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Eventually, over 4,000 miles from its source,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.38,0:31:41.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,亚马逊河汇入了大西洋\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}it empties into the Atlantic Ocean.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:48.86,0:31:53.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,亚马逊河每年会带来10亿吨的泥沙\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Amazon transports a billion tonnes of sediment a year,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.10,0:31:57.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,泥沙使得河水交汇成为一道显眼的风景\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}sediment clearly visible at the mixing of the waters
Dialogue: 0,0:31:57.06,0:32:02.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,一条巨大的支流 ——内格罗河在此汇入干流\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}where one massive tributary, the Rio Negro, flows into the main river.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.46,0:32:10.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,河水中的物种异常丰富\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Its waters are wonderfully rich.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:11.06,0:32:15.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,据统计 被命名的鱼类已达到3000多种\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}To date over 3,000 species of their fish have been described -
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.38,0:32:18.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这比整个大西洋的鱼类种数还要多\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}more than in the whole of the Atlantic Ocean.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.94,0:32:49.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,亚马逊河养育着丰富繁多的鱼类\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Amazon is so large and rich in fish
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.18,0:32:52.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,为淡水海豚提供了生存条件\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}that it can support fresh water dolphins.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.42,0:32:57.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些亚马逊江豚体型巨大  身长达2.5米\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These botos are huge - two and a half metres long.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:59.50,0:33:05.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们利用回声定位 在昏暗的水中探路和捕食\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In these murky waters they rely on sonar to navigate and hunt.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.06,0:33:26.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们一起合作把鱼群赶到浅水区\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They work together to drive shoals of fish into the shallows.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.94,0:34:29.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,亚马逊江豚是高度社会型动物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Botos are highly social
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.90,0:34:34.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在繁殖季节 会有一场激烈的求偶竞赛\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and in the breeding season there is stiff competition for mates.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.82,0:34:38.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,雄江豚会以独特的方式向雌江豚示爱\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The males hold court in a unique way.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.30,0:34:51.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们用长嘴捡起石块\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They pick up rocks in their jaws
Dialogue: 0,0:34:51.86,0:34:55.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,然后向自己的“心上人”炫耀\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and flaunt them to their attending females.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:59.46,0:35:03.58,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这或许是雄江豚展示自己 强壮身体和敏捷身手的一种方式\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Maybe each male is trying to show how strong and dexterous he is
Dialogue: 0,0:35:03.62,0:35:08.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以此来证明自己将是最好的父亲  雌江豚为了孩子就应该选它\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and that he therefore is the best father a female could have for her young.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:19.70,0:35:23.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,求爱成功后 它们便开始交配\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Successful displays lead to mating.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:37.90,0:35:40.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,即使像亚马逊河这般巨大的江河\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Even for giant rivers like the Amazon
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.74,0:35:46.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,流向大海的过程也并非都是平缓连续的\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the journey to the sea is not always smooth or uninterrupted.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.06,0:36:17.46,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,位于巴西和阿根廷边境的伊瓜苏瀑布\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Iguassu Falls on the border of Brazil and Argentina
Dialogue: 0,0:36:17.46,0:36:20.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,是世界上最宽的瀑布之一\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}is one of the widest waterfalls in the world -
Dialogue: 0,0:36:20.46,0:36:23.38,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,宽幅达1.5英里\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}one and a half miles across.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.62,0:36:35.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,瀑布每秒的水流量达到3000万立方米\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In flood 30 million litres of water spill over every second.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:21.02,0:37:24.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,所有世界上最大的瀑布\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}All the world's great broad waterfalls:
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.42,0:37:28.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,维多利亚瀑布、尼亚加拉瀑布  还有这里的依瓜苏瀑布\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Victoria, Niagara and here, Iguassu,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:28.18,0:37:32.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,都是位于河流的下游地段\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}are only found in the lower courses of their rivers.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.86,0:37:41.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在旅途的最后阶段\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In their final stages
Dialogue: 0,0:37:41.62,0:37:46.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,河道变宽 河水缓缓流过 平坦辽阔的冲积平原\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}rivers broaden and flow wearily across their flat flood plains.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:47.26,0:37:49.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这里是巴西 每到雨季\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Each wet season here, in Brazil,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:49.50,0:37:52.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,巴拉那河都会泛滥\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the Parana river overflows its banks
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.18,0:37:55.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,洪水淹没的地区相当于一个英格兰\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and floods an area the size of England.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.82,0:38:00.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,潘塔纳尔沼泽地\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The Pantanal -
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.14,0:38:03.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,世界上最大的湿地\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the world's largest wetland.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:09.94,0:38:14.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,缓慢的流水中生长着茂盛的水生植物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In these slow-flowing waters aquatic plants flourish
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.42,0:38:19.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,譬如有着2米宽叶子的王莲\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}like the Victoria giant water lily with leaves two metres across.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.06,0:38:46.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些水下森林正是 鱼类理想的“育婴”场所\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These underwater forests are nursery grounds for fish.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.46,0:38:53.90,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大约有300多种动物在此繁殖  其中包括红腹锯脂鲤\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Over 300 species breed here, including red-bellied piranha
Dialogue: 0,0:38:58.06,0:39:02.74,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,以及其它食肉动物 例如眼镜凯门鳄\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and other predators, like the spectacle caiman.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:28.14,0:39:31.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水边生长着高大的无花果树\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Ripening fig trees overhanging the water's edge
Dialogue: 0,0:39:31.70,0:39:35.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,为饥饿的鱼群提供美味食物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}provide welcome food for shoals of hungry fish.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:41.94,0:39:44.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,骚动引来了麻哈脂鲤\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The commotion attracts dorado,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.82,0:39:47.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当地人称之为“河中之虎”\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}known locally as the river tiger.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:55.30,0:39:57.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们穿梭于觅食的鱼群中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They patrol the feeding shoals,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:57.78,0:40:00.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,找准机会发动进攻\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}looking for a chance to strike.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:37.22,0:40:39.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有些鱼则守在一旁等待\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And waiting in the wings,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.10,0:40:41.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,时刻准备攻击任何受伤的鱼\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}ready to pick off any injured fish,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:41.94,0:40:43.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们就是锯脂鲤\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}are the piranhas.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:55.70,0:40:58.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们的进食速率极快\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The feeding frenzy quickly develops.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:16.18,0:41:20.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,锯脂鲤几分钟内便能 将一条活鱼啃得只剩下骨架\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Piranha can strip a fish to the bone in minutes.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:26.78,0:41:32.86,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,大量的鱼养活着大批聚集的水鸟\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Great numbers of fish sustain vast flocks of water birds.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:35.70,0:41:42.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,粉红琵鹭是潘塔纳尔沼泽地中的 650多种鸟类中的一种\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The rose-eared spoonbill is just one of the 650 bird species found in the Pantanal.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:49.78,0:41:55.26,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们将巢建在树干上  一群多达好几千只\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They nest alongside wood stocks in colonies thousands strong.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:22.98,0:42:25.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,眼镜凯门鳄在下面游荡\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Spectacle caiman linger below,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:25.66,0:42:28.66,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,等着食物从天而降\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}waiting for a meal to fall out of the sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:24.10,0:43:26.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,当江河最终汇入大海时\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}When rivers finally reach the sea
Dialogue: 0,0:43:26.22,0:43:31.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水流减缓 留下大量泥沙  堆成了三角洲\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they slow down, release their sediment and build deltas.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:32.66,0:43:36.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在孟加拉国 恒河与雅鲁藏布江的交汇处\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In Bangladesh the Ganges and Brahmaputra rivers join
Dialogue: 0,0:43:36.70,0:43:39.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,形成了世界上最大的三角洲\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}to form the world's biggest.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:41.38,0:43:45.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,每年大约有20亿吨泥沙在此沉淀\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Every year almost 2 thousand million tonnes of sediment
Dialogue: 0,0:43:45.82,0:43:50.22,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,从喜马拉雅山脉上 崩塌下来的土石最终归于大海\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}eroded from the Himalayas is delivered to the ocean.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:54.62,0:43:59.06,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,三角洲河口地带有一片 世界上最大的红树林\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}At the delta's mouth - the largest mangrove forest in the world,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:59.06,0:44:01.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,孙德尔本斯红树林\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}the Sundarbans.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:07.10,0:44:15.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这些特殊的树林遍及整个热带地区的潮间带  那里正是河流的入海口\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}These extraordinary forests spring up throughout the tropics in these tidal zones where rivers meet the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:24.86,0:44:28.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,食蟹猴是红树林的特有物种\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Crab-eating macaques are mangrove specials.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.50,0:44:39.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在印度尼西亚 这些猴子 过着一种独特的双栖式生活\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In Indonesia these monkeys have adopted a unique amphibious lifestyle -
Dialogue: 0,0:44:46.22,0:44:49.34,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们拣食落在水中的食物\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}they fish out fallen food.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.90,0:45:17.82,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在白天酷热难耐之时  猴群会利用水来给身体降温\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}The troop also uses the waters to cool off during the heat of the day.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:22.18,0:45:27.42,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,水道也是顽皮的小猴子们的游乐场\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}But the channels are also the playground for restless young macaques.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:32.90,0:45:37.18,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,有的小猴甚至已经学会潜泳\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Some of the young have even taken to underwater swimming.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:42.62,0:45:45.50,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们能在水下呆30多秒\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}They can stay down for more than 30 seconds
Dialogue: 0,0:45:45.54,0:45:48.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,而它们这么做似乎只是因为好玩\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and appear to do this just for fun.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:00.66,0:46:04.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,但是 这些在玩耍中学会的游泳本领\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Yet these swimming skills acquired during play
Dialogue: 0,0:46:04.62,0:46:10.02,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,将来会成为在红树林中 非常有用的生活技能\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}will certainly be useful  later in life in these flooded mangrove forests.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:18.22,0:46:21.94,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在较冷的地区 沉积在入海口的泥沙\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}In cooler climes, mud, laid down in estuaries,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.94,0:46:24.98,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,被大片盐沼水草覆盖\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}is colonised by salt marsh grasses
Dialogue: 0,0:46:25.06,0:46:28.78,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,成为地球上一处 最肥沃的野生动物栖息地\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and form one of the most productive habitats on the planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.82,0:47:05.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,40万只大西洋雪雁成群飞往 美国大西洋海岸的河口地带\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}400,000 greater snow geese flock to the estuaries along the Atlantic coast of the United States
Dialogue: 0,0:47:05.10,0:47:09.62,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,并在此休整 准备继续长途迁徙\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}to rest and refuel on their long migratory journeys.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:45.30,0:47:48.70,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,这是淡水之旅的终点\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}This is the end of the river's journey.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:48.74,0:47:51.30,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,它们共同抚平高山\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}Collectively they've worn down mountains
Dialogue: 0,0:47:51.34,0:47:53.10,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,把它们带向大海\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}and carried them to the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:53.18,0:47:54.54,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,在整个行程中\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}And all along the way,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:54.58,0:48:00.14,Default,NTP,0000,0000,0000,,淡水为地球带来了无数生机与富饶\N{\fs54\1c&HFFFF00&\b0}their fresh water has brought life and abundance to planet Earth.

